Introduction

XYZ Bank is a large and profitable bank in Saint Louis, Missouri. Like any large corporation, XYZ Bank has a very large and intricate infrastructure that supports its networking system. A Network Analyst recently discovered unusual network activity. Then, pouring over years worth of logs, their team of analysts discovered many instances of anomalous network activity that resulted in significant sums of money being siphoned from bank accounts. The Chief Networking Officer has come to us for help in developing a system that can automatically detect and warn of such known, as well as other unknown, anomalous network activities.

Key tasks completed

1. Determined that it is possible to differentiate between the labeled intrusions and benign sessions.

2. It is possible to identify different types of intrusions. We were successful in getting the attributes that contribute to the types of network intrusions in the data.

3. Developed and implemented a systematic approach to detect instances of intrusions in log files. Our system can take a new network_traffic log file and determine the existence of known patterns of intrusions as well as anomalies which may be indicative of new and unknown intrusion patterns.

4. Evaluated the detection power of our system.

5. Our intrusion detector can be used in real-time. It can receive data about a current session, and in seconds determine if it is likely to be an intrusion of previously seen type or an anomaly potentially signifying an unseen yet intrusion mode. We also give recommendations about what information should be exchanged via the user interface of the system.

Data Cleaning

In order to get started on classification and picking the best model for prediction, some of our data needed to be handeled. For example, there were some incidences in the data that needed to be removed such as a =0 value in attribute is_intrusion. This level was dropped from the variable is_intrusion which now contains two factors, 0 and 1. Also, in another binary factor variable su_attempted, there was a max value of 2 which changed to 1.Below, you can see the summary of the data and where these issues were seen.

Pairs Plot: All Variables

panel.cor <- function(x, y, digits = 2, prefix = "", cex.cor, ...)
{
    usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
    par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
    require(polycor)
    r <- abs(cor(x, y))
    txt <- format(c(r, 0.123456789), digits = digits)[1]
    txt <- paste0(prefix, txt)
    if(missing(cex.cor)) cex.cor <- 0.8/strwidth(txt)
    text(0.5, 0.5, txt, cex = pmax(1, cex.cor * r))
  
}

Classification Models for Benign and Network Intrusion Sessions

Differentiating between the labeled intrusions and benign sessions

The three classification models we chose were random forest, logistic lasso, and naive bayes. We have decided to choose these classification techniques because of their versatility in classifying mixed data.

classMetrics <- function(score, y, cutoff, 
                         type = c("all", "accuracy", "sensitivity", 
                                  "specificity", "ppv", "npv", "precision", 
                                  "recall")) {
  type <- match.arg(type, several.ok = TRUE)
  n <- length(y) 
  
  # Form confusion matrix
  score.factor <- factor(as.numeric(score >= cutoff), levels = c("0", "1"))
  confusion.mat <- table(score.factor, as.factor(y), dnn = list("predicted", "observed"))
  # Calculate all metrics
  acc <- sum(diag(confusion.mat)) / n
  sens <- confusion.mat[2,2] / sum(confusion.mat[,2])
  spec <- confusion.mat[1,1] / sum(confusion.mat[,1])
  ppv <- confusion.mat[2,2] / sum(confusion.mat[2,])
  npv <- confusion.mat[1,1] / sum(confusion.mat[1,])
  prec <- ppv
  rec <- sens
  
  metric.names <- c("accuracy", "sensitivity", "specificity", 
                    "ppv", "npv", "precision", "recall")
  metric.vals <- c(acc, sens, spec, ppv, npv, prec, rec)
  
  # Form into data frame
  full.df <- data.frame(value = metric.vals)
  rownames(full.df) <- metric.names
  
  # Return just the requested subset of metrics
  if(type[1] == "all") {
    list(conf.mat = confusion.mat, perf = full.df)
  } else {
    list(conf.mat = confusion.mat, 
         perf = subset(full.df, subset = metric.names %in% type))
  }
}

Random Forest

First, we performed random forest on our train data. Subsequently after, we predicted our model onto the test data where we obtained scores for our intrusions. Using a cutoff of 0.371 we were able to classify our scores as 1 or 0. 1 representing an intrusion and 0 representing a benign session. We then computed a confusion matrix between our predicted values to our observed test values which can be seen above. From the confusion matrix above, we obtained false negatives of 0 and false positives of 17. In addition, the misclasification rate is 0.0283333.

Finally, since the false negatives, observing an intrusion but classifying it as a benign session, is more costly in our situation, increasing sensitivity was a greater priority for our task. As seen above, we were able to obtain a sensitivity of 1 while simultaneously obtaining a specificity of 0.9681648 at a cutoff value of 0.371. Later, we explain why we use the cutoff value of 0.371 for all three of our models.

Logistic Lasso

#http://cs229.stanford.edu/proj2012/ChoiParkSeo-LassoInCategoricalData.pdf: cite

#Fit logistic lasso to train data
logit.train.x <- model.matrix(is_intrusion~., network.train)[,-1]
logit.train.y <- network.train$is_intrusion
lasso.network <- glmnet(logit.train.x,logit.train.y, family = "binomial", alpha = 1)

#Performing K-fold cross validation on sequence of model fits
network.lasso.cv <- cv.glmnet(logit.train.x,logit.train.y, family = "binomial", alpha = 1, type.measure = "auc")

#CV error curves
plot(network.lasso.cv)

#Index of the two Lambdas
lambda.min.index <- which(network.lasso.cv$lambda == network.lasso.cv$lambda.min)
lambda.1se.index <- which(network.lasso.cv$lambda == network.lasso.cv$lambda.1se) 

#Number of non-zero coefficients:
  #Lambda min
num.lambda.min <- network.lasso.cv$nzero[lambda.min.index] 
  #Lambda 1-SE
num.lambda.1se <- network.lasso.cv$nzero[lambda.1se.index] 

#AUC Values:
  #Lambda min
lambda.min.auc <- network.lasso.cv$cvm[lambda.min.index]
  #Lambda 1-SE
lambda.1se.auc <- network.lasso.cv$cvm[lambda.1se.index]

The second model we fit to our train data was logistic lasso. Logistic lasso is a method that performs variable selection. In order to determine the best model size, we performed 10 fold cross validation. As seen from the plot above, 10 fold cross validation returns several lambda values which include the minimum lambda value of 0.0000573 and the lambda value of 0.0007759 which is associated with the 1-Standard Error rule. The difference between the two lambda values is that the minimum lambda value has a higher AUC than the 1-SE lambda value.

However, while the AUC of the minimum lambda value is higher and better than the AUC of the 1-SE lambda value, we chose the lambda that corresponds to the 1-SE rule. This is because the lambda that corresponds to the 1-SE rule reduces the complexity of our model from 14 to 12 variables while maintaining a relatively similar AUC value. The AUC of the minimum lambda value is 0.9897614 and the AUC of the 1-SE lambda value is 0.9885628. Therefore, the AUC of both the curves are relatively close.

Clustering Types of Network Intrusions

Identifying different types of intrusions

After successfully classifying network sessions as benign and intrusions, we now move on to understanding patterns of intrusions in our system log. The system log is a set of data comprising of numerical and factor attributes. Clustering on factor attributes is not a straight forward task and hence we first convert our system log into a matrix using the matrix.model. The matrix is then scaled for clustering tasks to be carried out.

The two best known clustering methods are Hierarchical clustering and K-means clustering. We will apply both the clustering techniques to the system log which we have been analysing.

#getting data ready for clustering of intrusions

Hierarchical Clustering

In hierarchical clustering, we do not know the numbers of cluster we want. With hierarchical clustering the end result is a tree-like structure called dendogram. The dendogram allows us to view the clusters in a tree like structure with all 1 to n observations.

We first calculate the distance between observations in the dataset for hierarchical clustering. And then proceed with single, complete and average linkage hierarchical clustering.

#distances for Hierarchical clustering

The average linkage hierarchical cluster has been cut at a height of 4 to observe clusters and it also has a majority of values in the cluster 1 like the complete cluster.

The hierarchical clustering using the Euclidean distance is not able to cluster the data well as the majority values are being put into cluster 1 via all the linkage methods.

Single linkage clustering suffers from chaining, with only two close points we can get clusters and this results in spread out clusters. The clusters are not compact enough in this case.

Complete linkage improves on Single linkage and does not suffer from chaining, but gets hit with crowding. Here, the farthest two points are considered and hence the clusters tend to be compact but not spread out.

Average linkage handles the drawbacks of the single and complete linkage approaches but it has its own problems. The cuts in average linkages cannot be interpreted easily. The clusters can also change if we apply a monotone increasing transformation to our dissimilarity measure.

By seeing the above dendograms and the cluster results at a cut value of 4, we can say that the hierarchical clustering with euclidean distance is not doing a great job at identifying the types of intrusions in the dataset.

Gower Distance Hierarchical Clustering

We try improving the clustering better by using Gower distances in the next few hierarchical clustering steps. Gower distances work well for mixed datasets which contain factor and numeric values as attributes.

#http://www.sthda.com/english/articles/26-clustering-basics/86-clustering-distance-measures-essentials/ : Citation

#Gower distance Hierarchical clustering
gower.mat <- as.matrix(daisy(num, metric = "gower"))

#getting the distances in the Gower matrix
d.gower <- dist(gower.mat)

#displaying the Gower distance matrix
fviz_dist(d.gower)

The function daisy() is used to get the Gower distances, in data where there is a mixture of categorical and numerical values in features.

The fviz_dist() function from the factoextra package is used above to plot the Gower distance. The color levels are proportional to the value of the dissimilarity between observations: pure red if dist(xi,xj)=0 and pure blue corresponds to the highest value of computed Gower distance. Objects belonging to the same cluster are displayed in consecutive order.

We now proceed with single, complete and average linkage hierarchical clustering using the Gower distance that we have computed.

K-means Clustering

In K-means clustering, we seek to partition the observations into a pre-specified number of clusters. It is tricky to estimate the number of clusters from the onset, but K-means has been observed to perform well at clustering tasks with various mixtures of data.

The cluster plot above shows 4 clusters among the intrusions in the data. We have used a value of K=4 for the K-means clustering approach.

K-means clustering is a simple and elegant approach for partitioning a data set into K distinct, non-overlapping clusters. To perform K-means clustering, we must first specify the desired number of clusters K; then the K-means algorithm will assign each observation to exactly one of the K clusters.

The main idea behind K-means clustering is that a good clustering is one for which the within-cluster variation is as small as possible.

The K-means clustering works well for the network intrusion system log data and we are able to get 4 types of intrusions from the data.

#heatmap of clusters in the data
heatmap(num)

The heatmap above gives a good idea of how the various features contribute to the 4 different clusters that we have achieved via K-means clustering.

By carefully studying the heatmap and applying domain knowledge of networks we have come up with 4 types of intrusions as follows:

  • 1. The first cluster comprising of serviceftp_data, source_rate, transmission_rate and src_bytes comprise a Denial of Service attack. This is usually done to prevent the users to access the server.
  • 2. The second cluster comprising of flagS0, dst_bytes, guest_login and hot comprise a User to Root hacking attack as the hot and guest_login attributes are associated with the clusters.
  • 3. The third cluster comprising of flagS3, duration_transformed, logged_in, servicehttp make a Probing attack. The flagS3 in networking terms shows that a connection was established but the destination closed it. This attack is usually to check for open ports to get through into the system.
  • 4. The fourth cluster comprising of flagSF, protocol_typeudp, serviceprivate is a R2L attack. An R2L attack is an unauthorized access from a remote machine.
#https://www.statmethods.net/advstats/cluster.html : Citation

# Determine number of clusters
wss <- (nrow(num)-1)*sum(apply(num,2,var))
for (i in 2:6) wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(num, centers=i)$withinss)
plot(1:6, wss, type="b", xlab="Number of Clusters",
  ylab="Within groups sum of squares")

The Within groups sum of squares vs Number of Clusters plot confirms that 4 clusters exist in the intrusion data. Clusters 5 and 6 would not increase the performance of K-means clustering here.

Anomaly Detection

Developing and implementing a systematic approach to detect instances of intrusions in log files

From the above steps we were able to achieve classificatio of intrusions fron benign sessions and get different types of network intrusions as well. Now we explore the anomaly detection task.

Here we will be studying the various data points that are neither benign nor network intrusions, but should be analyzed for reducing risks and reducing costs of network intrusions in the bank network.

Mahalanobis Distance

We get the Mahalanobis distance by using the mahalanobis_distance function to compare the distance between each observation by its distance from the data mean.

\[ MD = \sqrt{(x-\bar{x})C^{-1}(x-\bar{x})} \]

where x is a vector of p observations,

\[ x=(x_1,...,x_p) \] and

\[ \bar{x} \]

is the mean vector of the data,

\[ \bar{x}=(x_1,.,x_p), C^{-1} \]

is the inverse data covariance matrix.

By using the bd_row fuction we identify which security log attributes in the data are driving the Mahalanobis distance.

state_vec %>% mahalanobis_distance("bd", normalize = TRUE) %>% bd_row(17, 10)

Next, the dimensionality is determined by finding the eigenvalues of the correlation matrix of the state vector matrix and retaining only those factors whose eigenvalues are greater than or equal to those produced by horns_curve. We use factor_analysis to reduce the state vector matrix into resultant factors. The factor_analysis function generates a list containing five outputs:

fa_loadings: numerical matrix with the original factor loadings fa_scores: numerical matrix with the row scores for each factor fa_loadings_rotated: numerical matrix with the varimax rotated factor loadings fa_scores_rotated: numerical matrix with the row scores for each varimax rotated factor num_factors: numeric vector identifying the number of factors

state_vec %>%
  horns_curve() %>%
  factor_analysis(state_vec, hc_points = .) %>%

Kaisers Index for Anomaly Detection

To evaluate the quality for a factor analysis solution Kaiser proposed the Index of Factorial Simplicity (IFS). The IFS is computed as:

\[ IFS = \sum{i}[q\sum{s}v_{j}s^4-(\sum{s}v^2_{js})^2]/\sum{i}[(q-1)(\sum{s}v^2_{js})^2] \]

where q is the number of factors, j the row index, s the column index, and vjs is the value in the loadings matrix. Furthermore, Kaiser created the following evaluations of the score produced by the IFS as shown below:

  • In the .90s: Marvelous
  • In the .80s: Meritorious
  • In the .70s: Middling
  • In the .60s: Mediocre
  • In the .50s: Miserable
  • < .50: Unacceptable

To assess the quality of our factor analysis results we apply kaisers_index to the rotated factor loadings and as the results show below our output value of 0.8250 suggests that our results are meritorious.

state_vec %>%
  horns_curve() %>%
  factor_analysis(data = state_vec, hc_points = .) %>%
  factor_analysis_results(fa_loadings_rotated) %>%
  kaisers_index()
## [1] 0.8250831

Correlation of factors with data features

We visualize the factor analysis results to show the correlation between the columns of the reduced state vector to the rotated factor loadings. Strong negative correlations are depicted as red while strong positive correlations are shown as blue. This helps to identify which factors are correlated with each security log data attribute. Furthermore, this helps to identify two or more security log data attributes that appear to have relationships with their occurrences.

fa_loadings <- state_vec %>% horns_curve() %>% factor_analysis(state_vec, hc_points = .) %>% factor_analysis_results(fa_loadings_rotated)

Estimating outliers in the data

We can use the Mahalanobis distances in a heatmap visualization to identify outlier values across our security log attributes and time blocks. The larger and brighter the dot the more significant the outlier is and deserves attention.

#heatmap mahalonobis distance
state_vec %>%
  mahalanobis_distance("both", normalize = TRUE) %>%
  as_tibble %>%
  dplyr::mutate(Block = 1:n()) %>% 
  gather(Variable, BD, -c(MD, Block)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(factor(Block), Variable, color = MD, size = BD)) +
  geom_point()

We use the rotated factor score plots to see the time blocks that appear to be outliers and deserve closer attention as they are anomalies.

state_vec %>%
  horns_curve() %>%
  factor_analysis(state_vec, hc_points = .) %>%
  factor_analysis_results(fa_scores_rotated) %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  dplyr::mutate(Block = 1:n()) %>%
  gather(Factor, Score, -Block) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(Absolute_Score = abs(Score)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(Factor, Absolute_Score, label = Block)) +
  geom_text() +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA)

This allows us to look across the factors and identify outlier blocks that may require further intra-block analysis. From the plot, we can clearly see that values 272, 14, 111, 166, 142, 32 are anomalies in the data.

Detection Power of the system

Evaluating the detection power of our system

The Kaisers index value for the anomaly detection system gives us a value of 0.8250 is a good performance metric as mentioned earlier. Combining this Anomaly Detection system with the classification of randomForest from the first task, we can get high levels of network intrusion detections.

The randomForest gives us high sensitivity while reducing the specificity, resulting in not failing to flag network activities that could be potential network intrusions. The value of the system in this domain is to study anomalous network behaviour rather than ignore it as a normal or non-intrusion attack.

The cost of not flagging a potential attack or anomaly is much higher than flagging a benign session as an intrusion and analysing it in detail. The goal in this project is to increase the sensitivity to lower costs of network intrusions in the banking system.
